Data Processing¶

Research questions: what are the most important determinants towards UBI?

individual Characteristics

  • age group
  • gender
  • Employment status
  • Left-right self placement
  • Members of Union
  • Net Household income
  • Feeling about income
  • Education

Control group2: belief or preferences

  • Economic Individualism
  • Economic fairness
  • Prefereces for redistribution

Control group3: welfare attitudes

  • Preventing poverty
  • Promoting equality
  • Increasing laziness
  • Burden or businesses
  • Strain on the economy
  • Supporting for targeting
  • Welfare chauvisism

Control group4: Media bais

  • Media bais X right_wing
  • Media bais X left_wing
  • Increasing laziness X right_wing

Contry level

  • support for UBI
  • net income inequality
  • unemployment ratw
  • social expenditure
  • social protection
  • material deprivation
  • welfare universalism index

# Calculating each individual's mean score over all 21 value items
valvars = ['v1', 'v2', 'v3', 'v4', 'v5', 'v6', 'v7', 'v8', 'v9', 'v10', 'v11', 'v12', 'v13', 'v14', 'v15', 'v16', 'v17', 'v18', 'v19', 'v20', 'v21']
df['mrat'] = df[valvars].mean(axis=1)

# Calculating each value
df['security'] = (df[['v5', 'v14']].mean(axis=1) - df['mrat'])
df['conformity'] = (df[['v7', 'v16']].mean(axis=1) - df['mrat'])
df['tradition'] = (df[['v9', 'v20']].mean(axis=1) - df['mrat'])
df['benevolence'] = (df[['v12', 'v18']].mean(axis=1) - df['mrat'])
df['universalism'] = (df[['v3', 'v8', 'v19']].mean(axis=1) - df['mrat'])
df['selfdirection'] = (df[['v1', 'v11']].mean(axis=1) - df['mrat'])
df['stimulation'] = (df[['v6', 'v15']].mean(axis=1) - df['mrat'])
df['hedonism'] = (df[['v10', 'v21']].mean(axis=1) - df['mrat'])
df['achievement'] = (df[['v4', 'v13']].mean(axis=1) - df['mrat'])
df['power'] = (df[['v2', 'v17']].mean(axis=1) - df['mrat'])

# Value items for each value
df['equality'] = df['v3'] - df['mrat']
df['broadmind'] = df['v8'] - df['mrat']
df['environ'] = df['v19'] - df['mrat']
df['helpful'] = df['v12'] - df['mrat']
df['loyal'] = df['v18'] - df['mrat']
df['wealth'] = df['v2'] - df['mrat']
df['socpower'] = df['v17'] - df['mrat']
df['capable'] = df['v4'] - df['mrat']
df['success'] = df['v13'] - df['mrat']

# Reorder columns
df= df[['achievement', 'hedonism', 'stimulation', 'selfdirection', 'universalism', 'benevolence', 'tradition', 'conformity', 'security', 'power']]

# Select the columns of interest
cols = ['achievement', 'hedonism', 'stimulation', 'selfdirection', 'universalism', 'benevolence', 'tradition', 'conformity', 'security', 'power']
df= df[cols]

# Remove missing values
df.dropna(inplace=True)

# Calculate the mean of each column
mean_values = df.mean()

df['self-enhancement'] = df['achievement'] + df['power']
df['openness to change'] = df['hedonism'] + df['stimulation'] + df['selfdirection']
df['conservation'] = df['security'] + df['conformity'] + df['tradition']
df['self-transcendence'] = df['universalism'] + df['benevolence']

# News about politics and current affairs, watching, reading or listening, in minutes

to_hours = lambda x: x / 60 if x not in [7777, 8888, 9999] else None

# create a new column 'political_news_hour' by applying the lambda function to 'nwspol' 

# how many hours spend on watching the news 
df_ess8['political_news_hour'] = df_ess8['nwspol'].apply(to_hours)

# Most people can be trusted or you can't be too careful, 0 = you can't be too careful, 10 = most people can be trusted
df_ess8['trust_in_people'] = np.where((df_ess8['ppltrst'] >= 0) & (df_ess8['ppltrst'] <= 10), df_ess8['ppltrst'], np.nan)

# Most people try to take advantage of you, or try to be fair, 0 = most people try to take advantage of me, most people try to be fair
df_ess8['fair_in_people'] = np.where((df_ess8['pplfair'] >= 0) & (df_ess8['pplfair'] <= 10), df_ess8['pplfair'], np.nan)

# Most of the time people helpful or mostly looking out for themselves, 0 = people mostly look for themselves, 10 = people mosrtly try to be helpful

df_ess8['helpful_in_people'] = np.where((df_ess8['pplhlp'] >= 0) & (df_ess8['pplhlp'] <= 10), df_ess8['pplhlp'], np.nan)

# How close to party, 1 = very close, 4 = not close at all

df_ess8['distance_to_party'] = np.where((df_ess8['prtdgcl'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['prtdgcl'] <= 4), df_ess8['prtdgcl'], np.nan)

# Placement on left right scale, 0 = left, 10 = right

df_ess8['left_on_scale'] = np.where((df_ess8['lrscale'] >= 0) & (df_ess8['lrscale'] <= 10), df_ess8['lrscale'], np.nan)

Economics Belief, Preferences and Welfare Attitudes¶

In [9]:
# Large differences in income acceptable to reward talents and efforts, 1 = agree strongly, 5 = disagree strongly
df_ess8['economics_individulism'] = np.where((df_ess8['dfincac'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['dfincac'] <= 5), df_ess8['dfincac'], np.nan)

# For fair society, differences in standard of living should be small, 1 = agree strongly, 5 = disagree strongly
df_ess8['economics_fainess'] = np.where((df_ess8['smdfslv'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['smdfslv'] <= 5), df_ess8['smdfslv'], np.nan)

# Social benefits/services place too great strain on economy, 1 = agree strongly, 5 = disagree strongly
df_ess8['strain_on_the_economy'] = np.where((df_ess8['sbstrec'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['sbstrec'] <= 5), df_ess8['sbstrec'], np.nan)

# Social benefits/services prevent widespread poverty, 1 = agree strongly, 5 = disagree strongly
df_ess8['preventing_poverty'] = np.where((df_ess8['sbprvpv'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['sbprvpv'] <= 5), df_ess8['sbprvpv'], np.nan)

# Social benefits/services lead to a more equal society, 1 = agree strongly, 5 = disagree strongly
df_ess8['promote_equality'] = np.where((df_ess8['sbeqsoc'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['sbeqsoc'] <= 5), df_ess8['sbeqsoc'], np.nan)

# Social benefits/services make people lazy, 1 = agree strongly, 5 = disagree strongly
df_ess8['increasing_laziness'] = np.where((df_ess8['sblazy'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['sblazy'] <= 5), df_ess8['sblazy'], np.nan)

# Social benefits/services make people less willing care for one another, 1 = agree strongly, 5 = disagree strongly
df_ess8['less_caring'] = np.where((df_ess8['sblwcoa'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['sblwcoa'] <= 5), df_ess8['sblwcoa'], np.nan)

# W5, 1 = Immediately on arrival, 5 = They should never get the same rights
df_ess8['welfare_chauvinism'] = np.where((df_ess8['imsclbn'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['imsclbn'] <= 5), df_ess8['imsclbn'], np.nan)

# Social benefits only for people with lowest incomes, 1 = stronly against, 4 = strongly in favour
df_ess8['support_for_targeting'] = np.where((df_ess8['bnlwinc'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['bnlwinc'] <= 4), df_ess8['bnlwinc'], np.nan)

# Against or In favour of a basic income scheme, 1 = strongly against, 4 = Strongly in favour
df_ess8['support_for_ubi'] = np.where((df_ess8['basinc'] >= 1) & (df_ess8['basinc'] <= 4), df_ess8['basinc'], np.nan)

Modelling¶

M1: Multilayer logistic modelling¶

Following the spirit of Choi (2021) and Mohring (2022), this paper also performs the fixed effects approach as an alternative to multilevel analysis for cross-national analyses.

Examing country-level fixed effect would help to exploring the variance caused by diffference between country. However, to perform the logistic regression, it's essential to handle missing values in your dataset. Removing all missing values from the DataFrame is one approach, but we should also consider the randomness of missing.

In [41]:
# Calculate the intraclass correlation
var_country = result.cov_re.iloc[0, 0]
var_error = result.scale
icc = var_country / (var_country + var_error)

print("Intraclass Correlation (ICC):", icc)

Intraclass Correlation (ICC): 0.05385067752832008

The Intraclass Correlation (ICC) is a measure of the proportion of total variance in the outcome variable that can be attributed to the grouping structure, in this case, the country-level. ICC values range from 0 to 1.

In your case, the ICC value is approximately 0.054 (rounded to 3 decimal places). This means that about 5.4% of the total variability in the outcome variable can be explained by differences between countries. The remaining 94.6% of the variability is due to differences within countries (i.e., individual-level variation) or other unmeasured factors.

Interpreting the ICC value depends on the context and research question. Here's a general guideline:

If the ICC is close to 0, it means that the country-level effect is relatively small compared to individual-level variation or other factors. In this case, including a random effect for countries may not be necessary or provide substantial improvements to the model. If the ICC is close to 1, it means that the country-level effect accounts for a large proportion of the total variance in the outcome variable. In this scenario, accounting for the country-level effect in the model is crucial to obtain accurate estimates and make appropriate inferences. In your case, the ICC value of 0.054 suggests that the country-level effect contributes a small portion of the total variance in the outcome variable. Depending on the context and research question, this might indicate that the focus should be on individual-level variables or other factors that explain more of the variation in the outcome. However, even small ICC values can be meaningful in certain situations, so it is essential to consider the context when interpreting the ICC value.

def update_age_group(age):
    if age == 990:
        return np.nan
    elif age in [70, 80, 90, 100]:
        return 70
    else:
        return age

df_lm['age_group'] = df_lm['age_group'].apply(update_age_group)

# List of basic human values
values = ['security', 'conformity', 'tradition', 'benevolence',
       'universalism', 'selfdirection', 'stimulation', 'hedonism',
       'achievement', 'power']

# Initialize an empty DataFrame to store the coefficients
coef_table = pd.DataFrame(columns=['value', 'coef'])

# Iterate through the basic human values and run separate logistic regression models
for value in values:
    # Create the formula for the logistic regression
    formula = f"support_for_ubi_dummy ~ {value}"

    # Fit the logistic regression model
    model = smf.logit(formula, data=df_lm).fit(disp=0)  # disp=0 to suppress output

    # Get the coefficient for the value
    coef = model.params[value]

    # Append the coefficient to the table
    coef_table = coef_table.append({'value': value, 'coef': coef}, ignore_index=True)

# Print the table with the coefficients
print("Coefficients for the 10 basic human values:")
print(coef_table)

def update_age_group(age):
    if age == 990:
        return np.nan
    elif age in [70, 80, 90, 100]:
        return 70
    else:
        return age

# validation curve 

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import validation_curve

# Create a Decision Tree classifier instance
dtc = DecisionTreeClassifier()

# Define the range of max_depth values for the validation curve
depth_range = np.arange(1, 11)  # Max depth values from 1 to 10

# Calculate the validation curve
train_scores, test_scores = validation_curve(dtc, X, ydummy, param_name='max_depth', param_range=depth_range, cv=10)

# Calculate mean scores
train_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
test_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)

# Plot the validation curve
fig1 = plt.figure()
plt.plot(depth_range, train_mean, label='Train')
plt.plot(depth_range, test_mean, label='Test')
plt.xlabel('Max Depth')
plt.ylabel('Score')
plt.title('Decision Tree Validation Curve')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Save the plot as an image
fig1.savefig('validation_curve_decision_tree.png')

In [161]:
def get_curve_data(ytrue, yprobs, pos_class_label):
    FPR, TPR, thresholds = roc_curve(ytrue, yprobs, pos_label=pos_class_label)
    rates = pd.DataFrame(dict(fpr=FPR, tpr=TPR))
    return {'rates': rates}
